Here's the full **testsmells.org 19-smell academic audit** for `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, with integration-test calibration applied (class is annotated `[TestCategory("Integration")]`).

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High     | 3           | 3              |
| Medium   | 1           | 1              |
| Low      | 0           | 0              |
| **Total**| **4**       | **4**          |

15 of the 19 catalog smells are **clean** — this is a reasonably healthy suite.

---

## Findings by Severity

### 🔴 HIGH — Conditional Test Logic

**Taxonomy:** *Conditional Test Logic* (testsmells.org #1)
**Test:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (line 94)

```csharp
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);   // path A
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);       // path B
}
```

**Problem:** Only one branch executes per run, so the other is permanently untested. The test always passes but may be silently verifying the wrong thing.
**Risk:** Hidden coverage gap — if `PremiumUser` logic breaks, this test will never catch it because it takes the `else` path.

**Fix — split into two explicit tests:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_WhenStandard_ReturnsName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");
    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_WhenPremium_HasDiscountRate()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve", discountRate: 0.1m));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com") as PremiumUser;
    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Sleepy Test

**Taxonomy:** *Sleepy Test* (testsmells.org #3)
**Test:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 82)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(3000);   // hard-coded 3-second wait
```

**Problem:** Adds 3 seconds of wall-clock time, is still non-deterministic (slow CI = flaky), and this remains a smell even under integration-test calibration because the delay is a blind wait, not a resource provisioning step.
**Risk:** Flaky failures in CI; suite slowdown scales linearly with test count.

**Fix — poll with a timeout instead:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay()
{
    var user = new User("dave@example.com", "Dave");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    while (!_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
    {
        await Task.Delay(50, cts.Token);   // fast poll, bounded timeout
    }

    Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
}
```

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test)

**Taxonomy:** *Unknown Test / Empty Test* (testsmells.org #4)
**Test:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (line 113)

```csharp
public void BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }
    // ← no assertion anywhere
}
```

**Problem:** This test passes even if every insert silently drops data. The name implies "no errors" but nothing actually verifies that — it's a false-confidence test.
**Risk:** False green — 100% pass rate with 0% verification.

**Fix — assert the observable side-effect:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count);
}
```

---

### 🟡 MEDIUM — Assertion Roulette

**Taxonomy:** *Assertion Roulette* (testsmells.org, extended catalog)
**Test:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (line 28)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);              // which failed?
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name); // this one?
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email); // or this?
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);          // or this?
```

4 assertions, zero message parameters. When one fails in CI, the stack trace points to a line number, but the failure message is generic (`Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<Alice>. Actual:<null>.`).

**Fix — add assertion messages:**
```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Auto-generated Id should be positive");
```

---

## Smells Verified Clean (15 / 19)

| Smell | Status | Note |
|-------|--------|------|
| Mystery Guest | ✅ Clean | In-memory SQLite — no external resources |
| Eager Test | ✅ Clean | Multi-method calls are expected for integration scope |
| Magic Number Test | ✅ Clean | `3` and `10` are contextually obvious (items just inserted) |
| Sensitive Equality | ✅ Clean | No `.ToString()` in assertions |
| Exception Handling | ✅ Clean | No `try`/`catch` in test methods |
| General Fixture | ✅ Clean | `_connection` and `_repository` used by all 8 tests |
| Ignored/Disabled Test | ✅ Clean | No skipped tests |
| Duplicate Assert | ✅ Clean | No duplicated assertions |
| Lazy Test | ✅ Clean | Each test targets a distinct behavior |
| Constructor Init | ✅ Clean | Uses `[TestInitialize]` correctly |
| Default Test | ✅ Clean | Class is properly named |
| Redundant Print | ✅ Clean | No print/log statements |
| Redundant Assertion | ✅ Clean | No tautological assertions |
| Resource Optimism | ✅ Clean | In-memory DB — no assumed external state |
| Empty Test | ✅ Clean | All methods have executable statements |

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Fix | Effort |
|----------|-------|-----|--------|
| 1 | Assertion-Free Test | Add `Assert.AreEqual(100, ...)` | ~1 min |
| 2 | Conditional Test Logic | Split into 2 typed tests | ~5 min |
| 3 | Sleepy Test | Replace `Thread.Sleep` with poll loop | ~5 min |
| 4 | Assertion Roulette | Add message strings to 4 asserts | ~2 min |

**Bottom line:** 4 tests out of 8 carry smells, but the 4 clean tests (`InsertUser`, `UpdateUser`, `DeleteUser`, `ListUsers`) are well-structured — clear arrange/act/assert, focused scope, appropriate assertions. The fixes above are all low-effort and would bring this suite to a clean bill of health.
